ccessdate=2 June 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Naagin 2''\n| [[Indosiar]]\n| <ref>{{cite news|url=https://media.iyaa.com/article/2017/03/sukses-dengan-naagin-indosiar-siap-tayangkan-naagin-2-3586993.html|title=Sukses dengan 'Naagin', Indosiar Siap Tayangkan 'Naagin 2'|last1=Arya|first1=Putri|publisher=Iyaa.com|date=19 March 2017|language=id}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Malaysia]]\n| [[Hindi language|Hindi]]\n| ''Naagin''\n| [[TV3 (Malaysia)|TV3]]\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/malaysia/utusan-borneo-sabah/20171113/282213716106856|title=PressReader.com \u2013 Connecting People Through News|website=www.pressreader.com|access-date=8 January 2018}}</ref>\n|}\nA Spoof to the series was also made by the youtube channel 'TheBroViews' named as \"Naagmoney\".\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDB title|5323298}}\n\n{{Colors Programmes}}\n{{Balaji Telefilms}}\n\n[[Category:Balaji Telefilms television series]]\n[[Category:2015 Indian television series debuts]]\n[[Category:Indian fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:Indian drama television series]]\n[[Category:Colors (TV channel) series]]\n[[Category:Hindi-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Rajasthan]]\n", "name_user": "Kaltenmeyer", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, replaced: woukd \u2192 would,typo(s) fixed: Meanwhile \u2192 Meanwhile,, youtube \u2192 YouTube", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naagin_(2015_TV_series)"}
{"title_page": "Edna Best", "text_new": "{{short description|British actress}}\n{{for|the social activist and war worker|Edna May Williston Best}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox person|\n| name          = Edna Clara Best\n| image         = Edna Best.jpg\n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Edna Best \n| birth_date    = {{birth date|df=yes|1900|3|3}}\n| birth_place   = [[Hove]], [[England]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1974|9|18|1900|3|3}}\n| death_place   = [[Geneva]], [[Canton of Geneva]], [[Switzerland]]\n| occupation    = Actress\n| years_active  = 1917\u20131959\n| spouse        = Seymour Beard<br>({{abbr|m.|married}} 192?; {{abbr|div.|divorced}} 1928)<br>{{marriage|[[Herbert Marshall]]<br>|1928|1940|end=divorced}}<br>{{marriage|Nat Wolff<br>|1940|1959|end=died}}\n| children      = 3, including [[Sarah Marshall (British actress)|Sarah Marshall]]\n}}\n\n'''Edna Clara Best''' (3 March 1900 \u2013 18 September 1974<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://projects.latimes.com/hollywood/star-walk/edna-best/|title=Edna Best - Hollywood Star Walk - Los Angeles Times|website=projects.latimes.com|language=en|access-date=2017-10-23}}</ref>) was a British stage and screen actress.\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Hove]], Sussex, England, she was educated in [[Brighton]] and later studied dramatic acting under Miss Kate Rorke who was the first Professor of Drama at the [[Guildhall School of Music and Drama]], London.\n\n==Career==\nEdna Best was known on the London stage before she entered films in 1921, having made her debut at the Grand Theatre, [[Southampton]], in ''[[Charley's Aunt]]'' in 1917. She also won a silver swimming cup as the lady swimming champion of Sussex. She appeared with husband Herbert Marshall in [[John Van Druten]]'s 1931 play ''[[There's Always Juliet]]'' on both Broadway and London.\n\nFor [[Gainsborough Pictures]] she starred in the [[melodramas]] ''[[Michael and Mary]]'' and ''[[The Faithful Heart (1932 film)|The Faithful Heart]]'' alongside her husband. \nShe is best remembered for her role as the mother in the original 1934 film version of [[Alfred Hitchcock]]'s ''[[The Man Who Knew Too Much (1934 film)|The Man Who Knew Too Much]]''. Her subsequent roles were a mixture of British and Hollywood productions. Among her other film credits are ''[[Intermezzo: A Love Story]]'' (1939), ''[[Swiss Family Robinson (1940 film)|Swiss Family Robinson]]'' (1940), ''[[The Late George Apley (film)|The Late George Apley]]'' and ''[[The Ghost and Mrs. Muir]]'' (both 1947) and ''[[The Iron Curtain (film)|The Iron Curtain]]'' (1948).\n\nBest received a nomination for an [[Emmy Award]] in 1957 for her role in ''[[This Happy Breed]]''. She had appeared on television as early as 1938, in a live production of the play ''[[Love from a Stranger (TV)|Love from a Stranger]]'', adapted from the [[Agatha Christie]] short story \"Philomel Cottage\" by [[Frank Vosper]].\n\n==Personal life==\nBest was married three times and divorced twice.\n\nHer first marriage, to William Seymour Beard, ended in divorce in 1928. The London Divorce Court gave Beard custody of the couple's twins (James and John Beard<ref name=dbmj>{{cite news|title=Edna Best Divorces Herbert Marshall, Weds an Agent|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1873&dat=19400208&id=BHIoAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EscEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5852,3440312&hl=en|accessdate=24 May 2015|work=Daytona Beach Morning Journal|issue=8 February 1940|page=3}}</ref>) in granting the divorce \"owing to the misconduct of his wife, Miss Best, with Mr. Marshall.\"<ref name=a>{{cite news|title=Miss Edna Best Divorced|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article49393736|accessdate=24 May 2015|work=The Advertiser|date=28 June 1928}}</ref> The \"Mr. Marshall\" referred to was actor [[Herbert Marshall]], whose divorce from Hilda Lloyd Marshall (\"owing to the misconduct of her husband ... with ... Miss Edna Best\") was granted in the same court session.<ref name=a/> Best later was married to Marshall from 28 November 1928,<ref>{{cite news|title=Actor Edna Best Divorces Marshall And Marries Wolff|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/2470452/the_lincoln_star/|agency=The Lincoln Star|date=7 February 1940|page=7|publisher=[[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = 23 May 2015}} {{Open access}}</ref> until 1940, and they had a daughter, actress [[Sarah Marshall (British actress)|Sarah Marshall]]. She married talent agent Nat Wolff on 7 February 1940, in [[Las Vegas]], Nevada. The judge \"who granted the divorce [from Marshall] after a five-minute closed hearing, performed the marriage a few minutes later.\"<ref name=dbmj/>\n\nBest suffered a stroke in 1959.<ref>{{cite news|title=Actress Suffers Stroke|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/2470426/the_decatur_herald/|work=The Decatur Herald|date=7 May 1959|page=1|publisher=[[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = 23 May 2015}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\nIn 1960, Best was inducted into the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] with a [[List of actors with Hollywood Walk of Fame motion picture stars|motion pictures star]] located at 6124 [[Hollywood Boulevard]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walkoffame.com/edna-best |title=Hollywood Walk of Fame - Edna Best |website=walkoffame.com |publisher=Hollywood Chamber of Commerce |accessdate=November 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nShe died in [[Geneva]], [[Switzerland]], in 1974, aged 74.\n\n==Filmography==\n{{div col|colwidth=26em}}\n* ''[[Tilly of Bloomsbury (1921 film)|Tilly of Bloomsbury]]'' (1921) - Tilly Welwyn\n* ''[[A Couple of Down and Outs]]'' (1923) - Molly Roarke\n* ''[[Sleeping Partners]]'' (1930) - She\n* ''[[Loose Ends (film)|Loose Ends]]'' (1930) - Nina Grant\n* ''[[Escape (1930 film)|Escape]]'' (1930) - Shingled Lady\n* ''[[Beyond the Cities]]'' (1930) - Mary Hayes\n* ''[[The Calendar (1931 film)|The Calendar]]'' (1931) - Jill Panniford\n* ''[[Michael and Mary]]'' (1931) - Mary Rowe\n* ''[[The Faithful Heart (1932 film)|The Faithful Heart]]'' (1932) - Blackie Anderway / Blackie's Daughter\n* ''[[The Key (1934 film)|The Key]]'' (1934) - Norah Kerr\n* ''[[The Man Who Knew Too Much (1934 film)|The Man Who Knew Too Much]]'' (1934) - Jill Lawrence\n* ''[[South Riding (film)|South Riding]]'' (1938) - Sarah Burton\n* ''[[Prison Without Bars]]'' (1938) - Yvonne Chanel\n* ''[[Intermezzo (1939 film)|Intermezzo]]'' (1939) - Margit Brandt\n* ''[[Swiss Family Robinson (1940 film)|Swiss Family Robinson]]'' (1940) - Elizabeth Robinson\n* ''[[This Man Reuter]]'' (1940) - Ida Magnus\n* ''[[The Late George Apley (film)|The Late George Apley]]'' (1947) - Catherine Apley\n* ''[[The Ghost and Mrs. Muir]]'' (1947) - Martha Huggin\n* ''[[The Iron Curtain (film)|The Iron Curtain]]'' (1948) - Mrs. Albert Foster\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Radio appearances==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Programme !! Episode/Source\n|-\n| 1952|| ''[[The United States Steel Hour#Theatre Guild on the Air|Theatre Guild on the Air]]'' || ''[[Love from a Stranger (play)|Love from a Stranger]]''<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kirby|first1=Walter|title=Better Radio Programs for the Week|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/2470060/the_decatur_daily_review/|agency=The Decatur Daily Review|date=16 March 1952|page=44|publisher=[[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = 23 May 2015}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1953|| ''[[The United States Steel Hour#Theatre Guild on the Air|Theatre Guild on the Air]]'' || ''Jane''<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kirby|first1=Walter|title=Better Radio Programs for the Week|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/2648547/the_decatur_daily_review/|agency=The Decatur Daily Review|date=11 January 1953|page=42|publisher=[[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = 19 June 2015}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n* {{IMDb name|0078923}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{Find a Grave|42051790}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Best, Edna}}\n[[Category:1900 births]]\n[[Category:1974 deaths]]\n[[Category:English film actresses]]\n[[Category:English stage actresses]]\n[[Category:English radio actresses]]\n[[Category:English expatriates in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:People from Hove]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:20th-century English actresses]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British actress}}\n{{for|the social activist and war worker|Edna May Williston Best}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox person|\n| name          = Edna Clara Best\n| image         = Edna Best.jpg\n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Edna Best \n| birth_date    = {{birth date|df=yes|1900|3|3}}\n| birth_place   = [[Hove]], [[England]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1974|9|18|1900|3|3}}\n| death_place   = [[Geneva]], [[Canton of Geneva]], [[Switzerland]]\n| occupation    = Actress\n| years_active  = 1917\u20131959\n| spouse        = Seymour Beard<br>({{abbr|m.|married}} 192?; {{abbr|div.|divorced}} 1928)<br>{{marriage|[[Herbert Marshall]]<br>|1928|1940|end=divorced}}<br>{{marriage|Nat Wolff<br>|1940|1959|end=died}}\n| children      = 3, including [[Sarah Marshall (British actress)|Sarah Marshall]]\n}}\n\n'''Edna Clara Best''' (3 March 1900 \u2013 18 September 1974<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://projects.latimes.com/hollywood/star-walk/edna-best/|title=Edna Best - Hollywood Star Walk - Los Angeles Times|website=projects.latimes.com|language=en|access-date=2017-10-23}}</ref>) was a British stage and screen actress.\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Hove]], Sussex, England, she was educated in [[Brighton]] and later studied dramatic acting under Miss Kate Rorke who was the first Professor of Drama at the [[Guildhall School of Music and Drama]], London.\n\n==Career==\nEdna Best was known on the London stage before she entered films in 1921, having made her debut at the Grand Theatre, [[Southampton]], in ''[[Charley's Aunt]]'' in 1917. She also won a silver swimming cup as the lady swimming champion of Sussex. She appeared with husband Herbert Marshall in [[John Van Druten]]'s 1931 play ''[[There's Always Juliet]]'' on both Broadway and London.\n\nFor [[Gainsborough Pictures]] she starred in the [[melodramas]] ''[[Michael and Mary]]'' and ''[[The Faithful Heart]]'' alongside her husband. \nShe is best remembered for her role as the mother in the original 1934 film version of [[Alfred Hitchcock]]'s ''[[The Man Who Knew Too Much (1934 film)|The Man Who Knew Too Much]]''. Her subsequent roles were a mixture of British and Hollywood productions. Among her other film credits are ''[[Intermezzo: A Love Story]]'' (1939), ''[[Swiss Family Robinson (1940 film)|Swiss Family Robinson]]'' (1940), ''[[The Late George Apley (film)|The Late George Apley]]'' and ''[[The Ghost and Mrs. Muir]]'' (both 1947) and ''[[The Iron Curtain (film)|The Iron Curtain]]'' (1948).\n\nBest received a nomination for an [[Emmy Award]] in 1957 for her role in ''[[This Happy Breed]]''. She had appeared on television as early as 1938, in a live production of the play ''[[Love from a Stranger (TV)|Love from a Stranger]]'', adapted from the [[Agatha Christie]] short story \"Philomel Cottage\" by [[Frank Vosper]].\n\n==Personal life==\nBest was married three times and divorced twice.\n\nHer first marriage, to William Seymour Beard, ended in divorce in 1928. The London Divorce Court gave Beard custody of the couple's twins (James and John Beard<ref name=dbmj>{{cite news|title=Edna Best Divorces Herbert Marshall, Weds an Agent|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1873&dat=19400208&id=BHIoAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EscEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5852,3440312&hl=en|accessdate=24 May 2015|work=Daytona Beach Morning Journal|issue=8 February 1940|page=3}}</ref>) in granting the divorce \"owing to the misconduct of his wife, Miss Best, with Mr. Marshall.\"<ref name=a>{{cite news|title=Miss Edna Best Divorced|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article49393736|accessdate=24 May 2015|work=The Advertiser|date=28 June 1928}}</ref> The \"Mr. Marshall\" referred to was actor [[Herbert Marshall]], whose divorce from Hilda Lloyd Marshall (\"owing to the misconduct of her husband ... with ... Miss Edna Best\") was granted in the same court session.<ref name=a/> Best later was married to Marshall from 28 November 1928,<ref>{{cite news|title=Actor Edna Best Divorces Marshall And Marries Wolff|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/2470452/the_lincoln_star/|agency=The Lincoln Star|date=7 February 1940|page=7|publisher=[[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = 23 May 2015}} {{Open access}}</ref> until 1940, and they had a daughter, actress [[Sarah Marshall (British actress)|Sarah Marshall]]. She married talent agent Nat Wolff on 7 February 1940, in [[Las Vegas]], Nevada. The judge \"who granted the divorce [from Marshall] after a five-minute closed hearing, performed the marriage a few minutes later.\"<ref name=dbmj/>\n\nBest suffered a stroke in 1959.<ref>{{cite news|title=Actress Suffers Stroke|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/2470426/the_decatur_herald/|work=The Decatur Herald|date=7 May 1959|page=1|publisher=[[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = 23 May 2015}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\nIn 1960, Best was inducted into the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] with a [[List of actors with Hollywood Walk of Fame motion picture stars|motion pictures star]] located at 6124 [[Hollywood Boulevard]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walkoffame.com/edna-best |title=Hollywood Walk of Fame - Edna Best |website=walkoffame.com |publisher=Hollywood Chamber of Commerce |accessdate=November 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nShe died in [[Geneva]], [[Switzerland]], in 1974, aged 74.\n\n==Filmography==\n{{div col|colwidth=26em}}\n* ''[[Tilly of Bloomsbury (1921 film)|Tilly of Bloomsbury]]'' (1921) - Tilly Welwyn\n* ''[[A Couple of Down and Outs]]'' (1923) - Molly Roarke\n* ''[[Sleeping Partners]]'' (1930) - She\n* ''[[Loose Ends (film)|Loose Ends]]'' (1930) - Nina Grant\n* ''[[Escape (1930 film)|Escape]]'' (1930) - Shingled Lady\n* ''[[Beyond the Cities]]'' (1930) - Mary Hayes\n* ''[[The Calendar (1931 film)|The Calendar]]'' (1931) - Jill Panniford\n* ''[[Michael and Mary]]'' (1931) - Mary Rowe\n* ''[[The Faithful Heart (1932 film)|The Faithful Heart]]'' (1932) - Blackie Anderway / Blackie's Daughter\n* ''[[The Key (1934 film)|The Key]]'' (1934) - Norah Kerr\n* ''[[The Man Who Knew Too Much (1934 film)|The Man Who Knew Too Much]]'' (1934) - Jill Lawrence\n* ''[[South Riding (film)|South Riding]]'' (1938) - Sarah Burton\n* ''[[Prison Without Bars]]'' (1938) - Yvonne Chanel\n* ''[[Intermezzo (1939 film)|Intermezzo]]'' (1939) - Margit Brandt\n* ''[[Swiss Family Robinson (1940 film)|Swiss Family Robinson]]'' (1940) - Elizabeth Robinson\n* ''[[This Man Reuter]]'' (1940) - Ida Magnus\n* ''[[The Late George Apley (film)|The Late George Apley]]'' (1947) - Catherine Apley\n* ''[[The Ghost and Mrs. Muir]]'' (1947) - Martha Huggin\n* ''[[The Iron Curtain (film)|The Iron Curtain]]'' (1948) - Mrs. Albert Foster\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Radio appearances==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Programme !! Episode/Source\n|-\n| 1952|| ''[[The United States Steel Hour#Theatre Guild on the Air|Theatre Guild on the Air]]'' || ''[[Love from a Stranger (play)|Love from a Stranger]]''<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kirby|first1=Walter|title=Better Radio Programs for the Week|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/2470060/the_decatur_daily_review/|agency=The Decatur Daily Review|date=16 March 1952|page=44|publisher=[[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = 23 May 2015}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1953|| ''[[The United States Steel Hour#Theatre Guild on the Air|Theatre Guild on the Air]]'' || ''Jane''<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kirby|first1=Walter|title=Better Radio Programs for the Week|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/2648547/the_decatur_daily_review/|agency=The 